
Build systems provide a `BackendBuilder` and wrap it in a `ProjectBuilder`.

The frontend compiles modules up to HIR and borrow validation.
The backend builder consumes those compiled modules and emits project artifacts.
That split is strict.

Backend builders don't load source files, discover modules, load or parse `config.bst`, perform semantic frontend compilation or write final output files directly.
They declare the build surface the frontend is allowed to see.

## BackendBuilder

[codeblock, $code("rust"):
    pub trait BackendBuilder {
        fn build_backend(
            &self,
            modules: Vec<Module>,
            config: &Config,
            flags: &[Flag],
            string_table: &mut StringTable,
        ) -> Result<Project, CompilerMessages>;

        fn validate_project_config(
            &self,
            config: &Config,
            string_table: &mut StringTable,
        ) -> Result<(), ProjectConfigError>;

        fn frontend_style_directives(&self) -> Vec<StyleDirectiveSpec>;

        fn frontend_surface(&self) -> BuilderSurface;
    }

    pub struct ProjectBuilder {
        pub backend: Box<dyn BackendBuilder + Send>,
    }
]

A backend builder declares these frontend-visible surfaces:

- source-backed packages
- binding-backed packages
- config keys
- style directives
- external import providers
- builder runtime packages
- supported source file kinds

It receives a validated `Config`, may validate backend-owned config keys and lowers compiled `Module` values into artifacts.
The frontend doesn't know the final project layout.
The backend doesn't know how raw source files were discovered.

## BuilderSurface

`BuilderSurface` is the build surface exposed to the frontend.
It carries typed registries, not loose callbacks or strings.

[codeblock, $code("rust"):
    pub struct BuilderSurface {
        pub binding_packages: ExternalPackageRegistry,
        pub source_packages: SourcePackageRegistry,
        pub config_keys: ProjectConfigKeyRegistry,
        pub external_import_providers: ExternalImportProviderRegistry,
        pub external_import_cache: ExternalImportProviderCache,
        pub external_import_resolution_table: ExternalImportResolutionTable,
        pub builder_runtime_packages: Vec<BuilderRuntimePackageMetadata>,
        pub source_file_kinds: SourceFileKindRegistry,
    }
]

`ProjectConfigKeyRegistry` is declarative Stage 0 metadata.
It lists allowed core and backend-owned keys plus value shapes so `config.bst` can reject unknown declarations, shape-invalid folded values and closed-domain string values before core fields are applied or backend settings are stored.

Source and binding registries stay separate because their resolution paths differ. Both carry shared `PackageMetadata`, whose independent `PackageOrigin` and `PackageBacking` axes let the frontend classify packages without conflating ownership with implementation. Config keys, providers and supported source kinds are builder surface too. Binding-specific lowering metadata remains with the binding and provider owners.

## Config compilation

`config.bst` is build-system-owned compile-time Beanstalk source.
It uses the frontend up to AST so config values can use normal compile-time constants, folded templates, core/builder imports and typed diagnostics.

It isn't compiled as a module.
It doesn't produce HIR.
It doesn't create runtime `start` semantics.
It doesn't export language-visible declarations.

Authored config entries must be known top-level compile-time constants declared with
`name #= value` or `name #Type = value`.
Plain top-level bindings are runtime Beanstalk syntax and are rejected in config.
Imported constants and support types may participate in config expressions, but imported declarations are support surface only and never become config entries.

Config may contain these support declarations:

- imports from Core or Builder packages
- type aliases
- structs
- choices

Config rejects these by design:

- project-local imports
- relative imports
- mutable bindings
- functions
- calls that require runtime behaviour
- runtime statements
- local helper constants that are not known config keys
- traits
- trait conformances
- trait incompatibility declarations
- standalone templates
- direct top-level const-template page fragments

For example, config rejects this active-module-root-only page-fragment form:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    #[$md:
        # Page title
    ]
]

Config-key constants can use const-record field projection when the expression fully folds.
Structured typed config values are still deferred.

## External import providers

External import providers are builder-declared hooks.
Stage 0 and import preparation use them to turn non-Beanstalk files into typed external package surfaces before AST consumes visibility.

Provider results may also carry registered runtime imports discovered while parsing the external source.
That is important for JavaScript imports: the frontend sees a typed package surface, while the backend later emits only the runtime glue and assets that reachable HIR uses.

Provider-capable discovery stays serial for now.
It mutates the external package registry, provider cache, resolution table and shared diagnostic string table.
Parallel provider-backed discovery needs deterministic provider deltas and ID remapping before it can be safe.

## Builder-runtime packages

Builder-runtime package metadata covers builder-owned virtual packages such as `@web/canvas`.
These packages are registered directly in `binding_packages`, then attached to module external-import metadata when reachable HIR references one of their functions.

This lets builder-owned packages share the same runtime asset and glue path as provider-created imports without pretending they were project-local source files.

## Source file kinds

Source file kind metadata lets builders opt into source assets that participate in normal source import discovery without becoming Beanstalk modules.
HTML registers Beandown `.bd` and plain Markdown `.md` content assets this way.

A supported source asset follows the same extensionless source import candidate path as `.bst` files.
Recognised but unsupported source kinds are rejected with typed import diagnostics.

Beandown and plain Markdown become ordinary synthetic `content #String` constants during header preparation.
Beandown nested templates with no explicit directive default to `$md` during ordinary AST template parsing.
They don't get a custom AST node, HIR, borrow-checker or backend path.

## Validation lanes

Project-specific config validation stays in `BackendBuilder::validate_project_config`.
It returns `ProjectConfigError` so normal user config mistakes remain typed `CompilerDiagnostic` values while infrastructure failures remain explicit `CompilerError` values.

Complex release optimisations should stay outside the fast frontend path unless correctness requires them.
This compiler is built for hot-reload development, so slow project-wide cleverness belongs behind a clear target or release boundary.

